MRI Acquisition
Image acquisition occurred at the OSU Wright Center for Innovation using a 3-tesla (T) MRI system (Ingenia CX, Philips Healthcare). To acquire brain images, a dStream head/spine radiofrequency (RF) coil was used. The following scans were collected of the brain: 1) High-resolution 3D fast-field echo (FFE) T1-weighted sequence (repetition time (TR) = 9.9ms, echo time (TE) = 4.6ms, matrix = 232 × 192, in-plane field of view (FOV) = 232 × 232mm, slice thickness = 1mm, number of slices = 150, number of signal averages = 1, flip angle = 8°, turbo field echo (TFE) factor = 192, scan time = 5min 20sec) and 2) 32-echo gradient and spin echo (GRASE) T2-weighted sequence (TR = 1200ms, TE = 10,20,30…,320ms, flip angle = 90°, refocusing flip angle = 180°, matrix = 224 × 90, in-plane FOV = 224 × 180mm, slice thickness = 1.5mm, number of slices = 80, number of signal averages = 1, scan time = 9min 30sec).
To acquire images of the cervical spinal cord (C2-C4), the following scans were collected: 1) merged fast-field echo (M-FFE) T1-weighted sequence (TR = 650ms, first TE = 4.1ms, number of echoes = 4, echo spacing = 7ms, matrix = 188 × 188, in-plane FOV = 150 × 150mm, slice thickness = 2.5mm, number of slices = 16, number of signal averages = 2, flip angle = 28°, scan time = 4min 10sec) and 2) 32-echo GRASE T2-weighted sequence (TR = 1500ms, TE = n*10ms, flip angle = 90°, refocusing flip angle = 180°, matrix = 240 × 196, in-plane FOV = 180 × 147mm, slice thickness = 2.5mm, number of slices = 16, number of signal averages = 1, scan time = 9min 10sec).
For individuals with SCI, MRI-acquisition occurred within 6 weeks prior to downhill training (range = 3d to 39d) and within 24 hours of the final training session. For uninjured control participants, two sets of data were collected within a single session. Scans of the brain and spinal cord were performed back-to-back, separated by changing of RF coils.

Generation of MWF Maps
Generation of brain and spinal cord MWF maps from T2 relaxation imaging used the latest non-negative least squares method (
Whittall et al., 1997
), implemented with an extended phase graph algorithm to correct for stimulated echoes (
Prasloski et al., 2012
). The T2 distribution of each imaging voxel was partitioned into short (<40ms), intermediate (40–200ms), and long (>1500ms) components using an in-house MATLAB code (MATLAB R2013b, MathWorks Inc) developed at the University of British Columbia (UBC; code requests:
https://mriresearch.med.ubc.ca/news-projects/myelin-water-fraction/
). The MWF is the sum of the amplitudes within the short T2 component divided by the amplitude sum of the total T2 distribution. Voxel-based MWF maps were generated for each participant.

Processing of Brain Imaging
Further processing of brain MRI data was performed as previously described by Lakhani
et al
(
Lakhani et al., 2017
). Here, we utilized the freely available FreeSurfer Software Suite v5.3 (
https://surfer.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/
) to perform all morphometric procedures, including automated cortical reconstruction and volumetric segmentation (technical details described previously (
Dale et al., 1999
;
Deoni et al., 2015
;
Fischl and Dale, 2000
;
Fischl et al., 2001
;
Fischl et al., 2002
;
Fischl et al., 2004
;
Lakhani et al., 2017
;
Reuter et al., 2010
;
Reuter et al., 2012
;
Salat et al., 2009
;
Segonne et al., 2004
)). Processing included motion correction and averaging (
Reuter et al., 2010
) of multiple volumetric T1-weighted images, removal of non-brain tissue using a hybrid watershed/surface deformation procedure (
Segonne et al., 2004
), automated Talairach transformation, segmentation of the subcortical white matter (
Fischl et al., 2002
;
Fischl et al., 2004
), intensity normalization (
Sled et al., 1998
), tessellation of the gray matter white matter boundary, automated topology correction (
Fischl et al., 2001
;
Segonne et al., 2007
), and surface deformation following intensity gradients to optimally place the gray/white and gray/cerebrospinal fluid borders at the location where the greatest shift in intensity defines the transition to the other tissue class (
Dale et al., 1999
;
Dale and Sereno, 1993
;
Fischl and Dale, 2000
). Images were automatically processed with the longitudinal stream (
Reuter et al., 2012
). Specifically, an unbiased within-subject template space and image was created using robust, inverse consistent registration (
Reuter et al., 2010
). Processing steps, such as skull stripping, Talairach transforms, atlas registration as well as spherical surface maps and parcellations were then initialized with common information from the within-subject template, significantly increasing reliability and statistical power (
Reuter et al., 2012
). Visual inspection of FreeSurfer surface reconstructions occurred at each stage of the longitudinal processing pipeline. Manual correction of errors included removing dura misidentified as cortex and re-processing the current and subsequent steps.
Linear co-registration occurred in three steps, using established methods by Lakhani
et al
(
Lakhani et al., 2017
) and Deoni
et al
(
Deoni et al., 2015
): 1) registration of the first echo from the T2 scan to the MWF map, 2) registration of the first echo of the T2 scan to the parcellated T1 anatomy, and 3) registration of the MWF map to the parcellated anatomy. All processing occurred on the same workstation, using the same software version (
Gronenschild et al., 2012
), and individualized intensity normalization was used to increase registration accuracy (
Sled et al., 1998
). The FreeSurfer-generated white matter parcellation map (
Salat et al., 2009
) was used to extract mean MWF from a priori identified regions of interest (ROI).

Processing of Spinal Cord Imaging
Spinal cord MRI data post-processing occurred as described by Liu
et al
(
Liu et al., 2020
). Spinal cord segmentation of the GRASE image occurred using the Spinal Cord Toolbox PropSeg tool (
De Leener et al., 2017
;
Yiannakas et al., 2016
), which generated a mask of the whole cord. Segmentation used the 16
th
echo of the GRASE image, because it has the greatest contrast between the spinal cord and cerebrospinal fluid. Visual inspections occurred and manual corrections to the mask were made when needed. The whole cord mask was then registered to the PAM50 template (
De Leener et al., 2018
) using a nonlinear transformation that involved a combination of center of mass rotation, affine, symmetric normalization, and bsplinesyn algorithms. This process obtained the warping functions used to transform the GRASE images and subsequently MWF maps into the template space. Visual inspection of all registered images occurred. MWF values were extracted from the PAM50 atlas labels.

MRI Data Analysis
For analysis of MWF data, subcortical white matter regions corresponding to areas known to be responsive to motor learning were identified
a priori
. Motor learning areas included white matter underlying the precentral, postcentral, caudal middle frontal, inferior parietal, and precuneus cortices, and the anterior and posterior regions of the corpus callosum (CC) (
Lohse et al., 2014
). Regions not expected to change following an eccentric-focused locomotor task were also identified
a priori
. Non-motor learning brain regions included white matter underlying the fusiform, inferior temporal, middle temporal, superior temporal, lateral orbitofrontal, lateral occipital, and lingual cortices (
Lohse et al., 2014
). We measured white matter plasticity in the cervical cord because frank demyelination, above-level atrophy, and neuroplasticity are localized here (
Freund et al., 2012
;
Liu et al., 2017
;
Raineteau and Schwab, 2001
). Due to the bilateral nature of the locomotor task, MWF data from right and left ROI’s were combined and averaged to calculate an overall MWF value for each region.
We determined reliability of MWF measures by calculating intraclass correlation coefficients (ICC). Regions with poor reliability (ICC < 0.5) were excluded from subsequent analyses (
Koo and Li, 2016
). Next, we determined whether individual MWF changes surpassed measurement error (
Beckerman et al., 2001
) by calculating the minimal detectable change (MDC) for each ROI using the formula MDC = SD * √(1 – r) * 1.96 as described by Forrest et al (
Forrest et al., 2014
). Here, SD represents the standard deviation (SD) of the difference between pre- and post-intervention measurements, r represents the ICC, and 1.96 is the 97.5% quantile of the standard normal distribution of a two-tailed test with the significance set at
α
= 0.05.
We compared the mean percent change of the downhill trained SCI participants (SCI+DH) with the mean percent change of the within-session data in the uninjured control group (Control) using a Mann Whitney U, nonparametric test to determine whether the mean percent MWF change within each ROI for the SCI+DH group exceeded the variability of the measure established by the Control group. Values are expressed as mean ± SD.

Experimental Procedures in Mice
Animal experiments were conducted with approval and in accordance with The Ohio State University Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee. Adult, male and female mice were group housed (3–5 per cage), fed standard chow
ad libitum
, and maintained on a 12-hour light/dark cycle throughout the experiments.

Generation of PDGFRα-CreERT2:mT/mG (mT/mG) Transgenic Mice
Because OPCs express platelet-derived growth factor receptor α (PDGFRα), we utilized Cre-inducible
PDGFRα
mice (
Rivers et al., 2008
) to generate inducible reporter mice as described by Hesp
et al
(
Hesp et al., 2015
). Heterozygous
PDGFRα-CreER
T2
mice were backcrossed with C57BL/6J mice for four generations, then bred with mice that express membrane-bound tdTomato on all cells prior to Cre-mediated recombination (B6.129(Cg)-Gt(ROSA)26Sor
tm4(ACTB-tdTomato,-EGFP)Luo
/J; Jackson Laboratories) (
Muzumdar et al., 2007
), to generate
PDGFRα-CreER
T2
:mT/mG
mice. Recombination was induced by oral tamoxifen administration (300mg/kg dissolved in corn oil) via gavage for four consecutive days. During tamoxifen treatment, mice were given prophylactic subcutaneous injections of sterile saline (2cc) and high calorie food supplements daily to prevent dehydration and weight loss. After recombination, cells transcribing the PDGFRα promotor down-regulate mT and begin to express membrane-bound green fluorescent protein (GFP), which is maintained for the life of the cell. Randomization into downhill training (SCI+DH) or unexercised control (SCI Unex) groups occurred immediately prior to injury. The disposition of all
mTmG
mice are described in
Supplementary Fig. 2
.

Experimental SCI Procedures
Incomplete spinal cord contusion was performed (
Faw et al., 2018
). Mice were anesthetized via intraperitoneal ketamine (138mg/kg) and xylazine (20mg/kg). Prophylactic antibiotics (gentocin, 1mg/kg) were administered subcutaneously prior to surgery. The spinal cord was exposed by removal of the T9 lamina. The Infinite Horizon device delivered a 75 kilodyne (kdyn) contusive force to the spinal cord. Paraspinal muscles were sutured, and the skin was closed using surgical clips. Mice received sterile saline (2cc) to prevent dehydration and recovered overnight in warm cages. Postsurgical care included daily subcutaneous injections of prophylactic gentocin and saline for 5 days and twice-daily manual bladder expression for the duration of the experiments. Animals with impactor force or displacement values that exceeded ± 2 SD from the overall mean were excluded from analyses.

Rehabilitation Paradigm
Mice received eccentric-focused, downhill treadmill training from 36 to 49 days post-injury, which consisted of quadrupedal stepping on a custom-built treadmill (Columbus Instruments) at the same 10% decline grade used for humans. Animals performed two, 10-minute bouts of downhill stepping separated by a 20-minute rest break in order to deliver 1000+ steps during each 20-minute session (
Cha et al., 2007
). Training speed was initially set at a comfortable pace (7.0m/min) and progressively increased within and between sessions to the fastest speed that did not degrade stepping performance. Training progression was individualized based on performance. Manual assistance was provided as needed for trunk stability during locomotion. For both mice and humans, training paradigm length (weeks) was set at 150% of previously established flat treadmill rehabilitation efficacy (Mice = 1 week; Humans = ~6 weeks) (
Hansen et al., 2013
;
Morrison et al., 2018
).

Open Field Locomotion
Locomotor recovery was assessed in the open field using the Basso Mouse Scale (BMS) (
Basso et al., 2006
) prior to SCI, at 1 and 7 days post-injury, and weekly thereafter. Two raters, blind to group assignment, rated locomotor performance over 4 minutes considering joint movement, weight support, plantar stepping, coordination, paw position, trunk and tail control. Scores range from no hindlimb movement (0) to normal locomotor function (9). To maximize consistency, screening of BMS scores occurred at 1 day post-injury and mice with 1 day BMS scores > 0.5 were excluded (
Hansen et al., 2013
).

Two-dimensional Kinematics
Fine characteristics of locomotion were assessed prior to SCI and 49 days post-injury using two-dimensional kinematics during flat treadmill walking as described previously (
Hansen et al., 2013
). Briefly, animals were anesthetized with 2% isoflurane, the left hindlimb was shaved, and bony prominences (iliac crest and greater trochanter) were identified by palpation and passive range of motion. Depilatory cream removed hair from bony prominences to maintain marker locations for the duration of the study. The lateral malleolus and fifth metatarsal head were marked with white paint immediately prior to assessment. We recorded 20 steady-state hindlimb steps per animal per timepoint at 60 hertz using a Nikon D3200 digital video recorder. Movies were uploaded and markers were digitized using PEAK Motus software. Due to movement of the knee joint under the skin during locomotion, a triangulation program estimated the knee position based on post-mortem femur and tibia measurements (
Goslow et al., 1973
;
Hansen et al., 2013
). Positional data (X,Y coordinates) were obtained at distinct gait phases: Initial Contact (E1; end of swing), Lift Off (E3; end of stance), and Flexion (F; mid-swing). End point kinematic data were compared between SCI+DH and SCI Unex groups using independent samples t-tests.

Thermal Sensitivity
Sensitivity to thermal stimuli was assessed at a consistent time of day at baseline and at six weeks post-injury using Hargreaves’ Method (
Hargreaves et al., 1988
) (Plantar Test Apparatus; Ugo Basile, Comerio, Italy). A male rater, blind to experimental groups, performed all testing, which eliminated sex effects of the rater (
Sorge et al., 2014
). Mice acclimated for 30 minutes prior to testing in individual clear plastic compartments (11cm × 17cm) with a glass floor. Infrared, radiant heat was applied to the plantar L5 dermatome through the glass until a withdrawal response occurred. A photocell on the heat source determined withdrawal and the duration (in seconds) of heat application (latency to withdraw). To prevent tissue damage, a 20 second maximum application was set. Mice were tested randomly with 5 trials per hind paw. The longest and shortest latencies were dropped for each paw before averaging the remaining latencies to yield a single withdrawal threshold for each mouse. End point latencies were divided by pre-injury latencies and scores are expressed as a percent of baseline. An independent samples t-test was used to compare SCI+DH and SCI Unex groups.

Tissue Processing
Mice were deeply anesthetized with ketamine (207mg/kg) and xylazine (30mg/kg) and transcardially perfused with 0.1M PBS followed by 4% paraformaldehyde (PFA) in PBS. Spinal cords were removed, including the cervical enlargement, divided into C1-C3 and C4-T1 segments, and a 6mm thoracic segment centered on the injury site (SCI groups) or T9 (Naive). Tissue was post-fixed in 4% PFA for 1 hour at 4℃, placed in 0.2M phosphate buffer overnight, then cryoprotected in 30% sucrose, before being embedded in optimal cutting temperature compound (ThermoScientific) and frozen on dry ice. Upper cervical and thoracic segments were oriented for cutting in the transverse plane. Lower cervical segments were oriented in the coronal plane to allow analysis along the length of axons. All tissue was cut at 20μm using a Microm HM 505E cryostat and stored at −80℃.

Immunofluorescence
To label the lesion border, axons, or paranodes, slides were thawed and rehydrated in 0.1M PBS, blocked with 4% bovine serum albumin with 0.3% Triton X-100 in PBS, incubated in primary antibody overnight (
Supplementary Table 2
), then in secondary antibody (
Supplementary Table 2
) for 40–60 minutes before rinsed in PBS and coverslipped with ProLong Diamond Antifade Mountant with DAPI (ThermoFisher).
To identify new oligodendrocytes, slides were thawed and rehydrated in 0.05M tris buffered saline (TBS), blocked with 10% fetal bovine serum with 0.5% Triton X-100 in TBS, incubated in primary antibody overnight (
Supplementary Table 2
), then in secondary antibodies (
Supplementary Table 2
) at room temperature for 60–90 min, rinsed with TBS then PBS before being coverslipped as above.

Digital Image Analysis
Fluorescent images were captured by confocal microscopy (Olympus FV1000 laser scanning confocal microscope; OSU Campus Microscopy and Imaging Facility). All images were blinded prior to quantification, which was performed by a single rater. Secondary antibodies at 633 or 647 wavelength were pseudocolored magenta during microscopy.
To quantify epicenter lesion area, spinal cord images stained for glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP) were imaged at 10x magnification and analyzed using stereological point counting in Stereo Investigator (MBF Bioscience). Using the Cavalieri method, a point grid was placed randomly over the epicenter section and intersections over tissue were identified as either spared or lesioned tissue, representing a point (p). Point counts for each section were converted to area estimates using the formula: Estimated Area = (∑
P
)*(
a/p
), where ∑
P
is the sum of points for an individual mouse and
a/p
is the area of each point. We calculated the percent sparing by dividing the area of GFAP
+
tissue by the total cross-sectional area. Animals whose percent sparing exceeded ± 2 SD from the mean were excluded from the study. Independent samples t-test compared percent sparing between SCI+DH and SCI Unex groups.
To determine the density and location of new oligodendrocytes in the cervical spinal cord, CC1
+
cells that fit the proper size and shape criteria for oligodendrocytes (~10μm, round/oval), and colocalized with GFP and DAPI (
Hesp et al., 2015
;
McKenzie et al., 2014
) were quantified throughout spinal cord hemisections located at C2 or C3. Spinal white matter was subdivided into dorsal columns, lateral, and ventral funiculi. To delineate lateral and ventral funiculi, a line was drawn from the midpoint of the ventral horn gray matter to the anterolateral sulcus at the edge of the tissue (
Chung and Coggeshall, 1983
). Cell counts were divided by the funiculi area, determined using ImageJ (
https://imagej.nih.gov/
), and are expressed as the number of CC1
+
/GFP
+
/DAPI
+
new oligodendrocytes per square millimeter (mm
2
). One-way ANOVA with Tukey’s
post hoc
test analyzed CC1/GFP/DAPI
+
cell density between Naive, SCI+DH, and SCI Unex groups.
To quantify oligodendrocyte lineage cell and axon interactions, GFP
+
/neurofilament (NF)
+
axon segments were quantified from high magnification (60x) images in the gracile tract of horizontally cut, cervical cord (C4-T1) tissue sections. Axon contacts were counted if GFP labeling surrounded NF
+
axons (in the same plane of focus) over at least a 5μm distance. Quantifications are expressed as the number of GFP
+
/NF
+
axon segments per mm
2
and analyzed between Naive, SCI+DH, and SCI Unex groups using a one-way ANOVA with Tukey’s
post hoc
test. Representative optical z-stacks were acquired at high magnification (180x) to illustrate GFP
+
processes wrapping NF
+
axons.
Contactin-associated protein (Caspr)
+
paranodes in the gracile tract of the cervical enlargement (C4-T1) were quantified as a surrogate measure of functional myelin. High magnification (80x) images were batch processed using MIPAR Image Analysis Software (Worthington, OH). Briefly, a threshold of positive labeling was determined for Caspr
+
labeling. Caspr
+
profiles were counted and binned into short (0.5–1.99μm) or long (2.0–19.0μm) profiles. The number of short and long profiles are expressed as a percent of total Caspr
+
profiles. Between-group analysis was performed using one-way ANOVA with Tukey’s
post hoc
test.

Statistics
Data from human participants are expressed as either individual values or mean ± SD. For within-subject comparisons, individual differences between pre- and post-training MWF values were compared to the calculated MDC for brain and spinal cord ROIs. Levene’s test showed there was not a statistically significant difference in variances between SCI + DH and Control groups. As such, we proceeded with between-group comparisons using a Mann-Whitney U, nonparametric test. For animal experiments, values are expressed as mean ± standard error of the mean (SEM). Individual data points > 2 SD above or below the mean were considered outliers and excluded from subsequent analyses. Between-group comparisons were made using either independent samples t-test or one-way ANOVA with Tukey’s
post hoc
testing. Relationships between functional and immunohistochemical measures were determined using Pearson’s correlation. All comparisons occurred using GraphPad Prism statistical software. Significance was set at
α
≤ 0.05 for all statistical tests.

Data availability
The data that support the findings of this study are available from the corresponding author upon reasonable request.

4.1. Lentivirus
pLenti-GIII-CMV-RFP-2A-Puro lentiviral vector with Nkx6.1-RFP (9947 bps) gene insert was purchased from Applied Biological Materials Inc. (Cat. #
LV476460
). The expression of Nkx6.1 and RFP is under the control of the promoter of CMV and SV40, respectively. The presence of a gene in the lentiviral vector was verified using PCR followed by gel electrophoresis. A lentiviral vector expressing only RFP was used as a negative control (lenti-Ctrl-RFP). Human Embryonic Kidney (HEK293T) cells were cultured in high glucose Dulbecco's Modified Eagle Media (DMEM) supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS), 1% nonessential amino acid (NEAA), and 1% Glutamax. Once the HEK293T cells were about 50%–60% confluent, they were transfected with target vector (lenti-Nkx6.1-RFP or lenti-Ctrl-RFP), envelope plasmid (pMD2.G/VSVG, Addgene 12259), and 3rd generation packaging plasmids (pMDLg/pRRE, Addgene 12251 and pRSV-Rev, Addgene 12253). The virus-containing supernatant was collected at two- and four-days post-transfection. Once all supernatant was collected on day two, fresh media was added to the cells. Viral particles were concentrated by polyethylene glycol 6000 (PEG6000) method(
Kutner et al., 2009
) and titer was determined by infecting HEK293T cells (
Kutner et al., 2009
).

4.2. Lateral hemisection spinal cord injury (SCI) and lentivirus injection
All experimental protocols were approved by the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) and the Institutional Biosafety Committee at Rutgers University. All animal work was conducted in accordance with relevant guidelines and regulations of the IACUC. Young adult C57BL/6 mice (8–12 weeks-old) were used for this study. Mice (both males and females) were kept at a 12-h light/dark cycle and were blindly and randomly chosen for each treatment condition. Animals were divided into the following groups (3 animals/group): (1) the sham group (the skin and muscle were cut to expose the spine, but SCI was not performed), (2) mice received SCI and lenti-Ctrl-RFP treatment (SCI + Ctrl), and (3) mice received SCI and lenti-Nkx6.1-RFP treatment (SCI + Nkx6.1). For SCI groups, a lateral hemisection was performed by first exposing the spinal cord around T9-T10 by laminectomy and then laterally cut on the left side of the spinal cord from the midline to the end. Immediately after the SCI, two injections of 1.0 μl of lentiviral particles (1 × 10
7
TU/ml) each at ~1 mm rostral and caudal to the lesion site, respectively. The needle was kept in place for 2–3 min after the injection to avoid backflow and allow virus diffusion into the tissue. The wound was then sealed by stitching the muscle and 2–3 clips on the skin. After surgery, animals from all three groups subcutaneously received painkiller (1 mg/kg Meloxicam) and antibiotics (50 mg/kg Cefazoline). Completeness of the hemisection was determined by the observation of paralysis in the left hind limb at the day-post injury (0 DPI) and 1 DPI.

4.3. Behavioral/locomotor assessment
Locomotion behavior of each animal was evaluated based on the Basso Mouse Scale (BMS) from an open field test (
Basso et al., 2006
). BMS scale ranges from 0 (completely paralyzed) to 9 (normal). The BMS score assessment was given 4 min of observation per animal by three independent observers who are blinded to the type of treatment. The BMS assessment was performed once before the surgery and then twice a week until 56 DPI.

4.4. Tissue processing
Spinal cord tissues were harvested at 3, 14, 35, and 56 DPI (n = 3/group/time point). At each time point, mice were intracardially perfused with 1× (v/v) sterile phosphate buffer saline followed by 4% (w/v) paraformaldehyde (PFA). About 5–6 mm of the spinal cord tissue containing the injury and injection sites was removed and fixed overnight with 4% PFA. The next day, fixed tissue was washed with 1× PBS and transferred to 30% (w/v) sucrose for dehydration for about 24 h. Dehydrated tissue was embedded using Tissue-Tek® optimum cutting temperature (O.C.T.) and stored at −80 °C. At each time point, tissues were sectioned on the sagittal plane at 12 μm thickness using a cryostat (ThermoScientific).

4.5. Immunohistochemistry (IHC)
IHC was performed based on a previously established protocol with minor modifications (
Li et al., 2016
). The sections were treated with cold methanol for 10 mins at room temperature, followed by incubating samples with blocking solution (0.05% Triton X-100, 2% donkey serum, and 3% bovine serum albumin (BSA)) to reduce background signal. Then, samples were incubated with primary antibodies (
Table S1
) in 1× (v/v) phosphate buffer saline (PBS) overnight at 4 °C. The next day, samples were washed with 1× PBS and incubated with secondary antibodies (
Table S1
) for 1 h at room temperature. Lastly, samples were washed with 1× PBS and incubated with DAPI (200 ng/ml) for 5 mins followed by the final wash and the slides were sealed with Cytoseal 60 (ThermoFisher Scientific 8310–4).

4.6. Image analysis
For image analysis, at least five sections from each slide (each with different antibodies)/animal were analyzed. Images were captured at the same exposure and threshold, and at the same intensity per condition using Zeiss LSM 800 confocal microscope or Zeiss AxioVision Imager A.1. The automatic cell counter in ImageJ (
Rueden et al., 2017
;
Schneider et al., 2012
) was used to count the total number of cells. Colabeled cells with cell type-specific markers and viral marker RFP were counted manually in separate RGB channels and with the following stereological considerations: 1) systematic and random sampling; 2) calculation of total cell numbers instead of signal densities, 3) counting of cells with aid from DAPI staining, not cell profiles, and 4) specific staining to identify the cells of interest. Data were presented as the mean ± standard error of the mean (SEM). Statistical significance between two conditions was calculated by Student's
t
-test and multi-group comparisons were performed using one-way ANOVA, followed by Tukey post-hoc test. A
p
-value of less than 0.05 was considered statistically significant.

4.7. RNA isolation
For RNA isolation, about 5 mm small region of the spinal cord tissue (containing the injury and the injection site) were extracted at 3 and 35 DPI, to reduce the heterogeneity due to the treatment and no treatment. At least 3 samples for each condition per timepoint were harvested. Total RNA from spinal cord tissue was preserved by fast freezing the tissue samples in liquid nitrogen. Total RNA was isolated from spinal cord tissue using RNeasy Lipid Tissue Mini kit (Qiagen, #74804) using the manufacturer's protocol. Total RNA was treated with DNase I (Qiagen) to eliminate genomic DNA contamination. The concentration and the quality of the total RNA were determined by NanoDrop Lite Spectrophotometer (ThermoScientific).

4.8. Real-time quantitative PCR (qPCR) analysis
From the total RNA, complementary DNA (cDNA) was synthesized using Superscript III First-Strand Synthesis System (Invitrogen, #18080051) using the manufacturer's protocol. qPCR was performed with Power SYBR™ Green PCR Master Mix and gene-specific primers (
Table S2
) using StepOnePlus Real-Time PCR system (Applied Biosystem). Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase (GAPDH) was used as a housekeeping gene. The Livak method was used to calculate the fold change of SCI + Ctrl and SCI + Nkx6.1 groups normalized to the sham group.

4.9. Library preparation and RNA-seq analysis
Quality control of the total RNA (using RNA 6000 Nano chip on the 2100 Bioanalyzer), library preparation (Illumina MiSeq) and RNA-Seq were performed by Admera Health (South Plainfield, NJ). The RNA-Seq was performed at 3 DPI and 35 DPI (n = 3/group/time point) using Illumina MiSeq using the manufacturer's protocol. Each sample was sequenced as paired-end (2 × 150 bp) on the Illumina MiSeq platform and generated a total of 40 million reads per sample.
Quality of the raw fastq file was assessed using the FastQC (
http://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/fastqc/
). Once the sample passed quality control (QC) all sequences were aligned to the mouse reference genome, mm10, using STAR (version 2.0;
Dobin et al., 2013
). The raw read counts were assembled as a matrix using HTSeq (version 0.6.0;
Anders et al., 2015
) and normalized using the DESeq2 (
Anders and Huber, 2010
;
Love et al., 2014
), a R/Bioconductor package. Next, DESeq2 was used to call for differential expressed gene (DEGs;
p
< 0.05) from the count matrix. The downstream pathway analysis was carried out using the Ingenuity Pathway Analysis (IPA, QIAGEN, Inc.,
https://www.qiagenbioinformatics.com/products/ingenuity-pathway-analysis
;
Kramer et al., 2014
).

Experimental design
A timeline for the experiments is shown in
Figure 1A
. Animals were trained to walk across the horizontal ladder. Animals were then bilaterally implanted with epidural electrodes over the M1 forelimb representation for chronic daily stimulation. Rats received a C4 moderate contusion (200 kdyn). After 2 weeks of recovery, animals were randomly assigned to a group that received 10 days of dual M1 and tsDCS electrical stimulation, followed by 6 weeks of rehab on the horizontal ladder. The second group received no stimulation for 10 days followed by 6 weeks of rehab. Forelimb motor performance was assayed on the horizontal ladder task once a week during rehab and for 2 additional weeks to determine persistence of effects. CST and PA axons were traced for histological analysis.
