Animals
A total of 19 female Sprague-Dawley rats (225–250g) were used for this study; 15 were used for the final analysis. Of the 4 animals that were excluded, 3 did not show clear spinal bruising after the contusion nor did they exhibit overt forelimb impairment, and 1 animal had cortical electrode malfunction after 3 days of stimulation. All surgeries were performed under aseptic conditions and general anesthesia using oxygen (0.8mL) and isoflurane, 5% for induction and 2.5% for maintenance throughout surgery. All experiments were approved by the City University of New York Advanced Science Research Center Institute of Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC).

C4 Contusion
A longitudinal incision was made from the base of the skull to T2. Overlying tissue was bluntly dissected to expose the vertebrae and a laminectomy was performed at C4. Clamp forceps, attached to the arms of the Infinite Horizon (IH) Spinal Impactor, were fixed into the transverse foramens of C3 and C5 in order to stabilize the spine and prevent spinal compression during the impact. The impact probe (3.5mm diameter tip) was lowered to touch the surface of C4 dura while ensuring a clear path without contacting adjacent bony structures. The probe was raised 3.9mm and impact was set at 200 kdyns with 0 dwell time, which typically results in clear bilateral bruising of the spinal cord (
Anderson et al., 2009
;
Zareen et al., 2017
) . After the contusion, we typically observed a midline petechial hemorrhage at the impact site and bruises on each side of the impact. After the impact, overlaying neck muscles and skin were sutured in layers. Rats were given subcutaneous injections of buprenorphine (0.03mg/kg), cephazolin (10mg/kg) and lactated ringer’s solution (5mL) and placed over a heating pad until awoken and conscious. Buprenorphine was administered for 2 more days post-surgery while Ringer’s solution and a high calorie food supplement (STAT; 10mL/day) were given for 7 days post-surgery or until animal was able to self-feed. All animals start to weight bear using their front limbs and self-feed by 7–8 days after SCI.

Bilateral M1 Electrode Implantation
The procedure for M1 electrode implantation was similar to our previously published study (
Zareen et al., 2017
). Electrode implantation was performed before obtaining baseline error rate. Animals were placed in a stereotaxic frame and an incision along the head was made to expose the skull. Overlaying connective tissue was removed and square craniotomy, approximately 0.5cm x 0.5cm in size, was made over the right and left forelimb areas of M1 using a dental drill with a 0.9mm diameter stainless steel burr (Fine Science Tools). Three-channel stainless steel epidural electrodes (length: 8mm long, diameter 0.005”) (PlasticsOne, Inc), bent to form an L-shape to increase contact area over the distal forelimb region of M1 were bilaterally placed on the dura overlying each M1 forelimb representation, at coordinates AP: 1.5–2.0 and ML: 3.0–3.5, with respect to the bregma. Dental acrylic cement was applied over the skull and the electrodes. The acrylic cement covering the craniotomies and electrodes was fixed in place by 4 stainless steel screws (3.2 mm; Plastics1, Inc); 2 inserted on both sides of the lambda, and 2 over the frontal sinus bone.

M1 iTBS + Cathodal tsDCS
We used the same iTBS+tsDCS protocol as in our previous experiments (
Yang et al., 2019
;
Zareen et al., 2017
) (
Figure 1B
). As animals moved freely in their cage, implanted M1 electrodes delivered phasic iTBS at 75% of motor threshold. Motor threshold was determined daily using multi-pulse stimulation (0.2ms biphasic pulse, 333 Hz, 45 ms duration) while the animal was held gently and its forelimbs were free to move in response to stimulation (
Carmel et al., 2014
;
Carmel and Martin, 2014
). The current was increased from 0 mA to the current that evoked a contra movement. We typically repeated this but from slightly above threshold and reducing the current to a current that no longer produced a movement. The iTBS pattern consisted of a burst of 3 pulses with an interstimulus interval of 50ms, repeated 10 times for 2 seconds, followed by 8 seconds of no stimulation. This was repeated 20 times for a total of 600 pulses which was referred to as a “block.” The stimulation protocol included 5 blocks of iTBS over a period of 27 minutes, with 2 minutes of no stimulation between each block, for a total of 3000 pulses each day. This specific protocol was modelled after human transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) studies, showing its efficacy in enabling long term potentiation (
Huang et al., 2005
;
Song et al., 2016
). Since iTBS threshold was set at 75%, there were no noticeable movements elicited by the stimulation during the treatment period.
Concomitant with iTBS was 27 minutes of continuous cathodal tsDCS. tsDCS was delivered through 2 percutaneous hydrogel electrodes (PALS; North Coast Medical), the cathode (1.4cm x 4cm) was placed dorsally extending over C4-T2 and the anode (2cm x 2 cm) over the chest. The dorsal surface of the neck and the chest were shaved and depilated (Nair) on day 1 and day 5 of stimulation. This placement was in accordance with results from Finite Element Modelling, which predicted the area of the spinal cord that receives maximal current flow within the cervical enlargement (
Song et al., 2015
;
Zareen et al., 2017
). Electric current was delivered using a programmable waveform generator (A-M Systems, model 3800) and stimulus isolation units (A-M Systems, model 3820). Rats wore a custom-made Velcro jacket to hold the electrodes in place on the skin surface as they were freely moving in their cage. tsDCS intensity was ramped up from 0 to 1.5mA (3 × 10
−3
mA/mm
2
) over a 2.5 second period, and after 27 mins of stimulation was ramped back to 0 over 2.5 seconds. Electrodes were covered with conductive gel before each use to enhance current flow and reduce skin irritation during the treatment. No rats showed signs of discomfort or skin damage during or following the stimulation.

Horizontal Ladder Training
Prior to training, animals were handled for 2 days to acclimate them to contact with the experimenters. Over the course of 2 weeks prior to injury, rats were trained to walk across a 2-foot horizontal ladder from one end to the other and jump in their home cage, which was placed at the end of the ladder. Animals were given sugar water at the end of each run for motivation. In order for rats to get accustomed to the task, they were first trained to walk across the ladder without gaps between the rungs, followed by removal of every other rung and finally alternating between single and double spaces between the rungs. Each training day consisted of 24 runs across the ladder and the order of the rungs was changed every 12 runs to prevent rats from memorizing limb placement. After 2 weeks of training, a baseline score for forelimb error rate was obtained by videotaping forelimb placement on the rungs for each of the 24 runs (Sony Handycam FDR-AX33 Digital Camcorder). By watching the videos in slow motion, we were able to discern if the paw grasped the rung (correct), was too far forward with the wrists placed over the rung, opposed to grasped (overstep), too far behind the rung with only the digits placed over the rungs (under step), or a missed step (rat’s limb falls into the space between the rungs). The number of oversteps, under steps and misses were added and divided by the total number of steps for each limb to obtain a total percent error rate. Animals were trained until forelimb error rate was equal to or less than 15% (
Metz and Whishaw, 2002
;
Yang et al., 2019
;
Zareen et al., 2017
).

Rehabilitation
Rehab on the horizontal ladder started after completion of 10 days of iTBS + tsDCS or 10 days of no stimulation so that both groups began rehab at the same time post-injury. Rehab consisted of 24 runs on the ladder, 5 days a week for 6 weeks. As with training, during rehab the ladder rungs were spaced irregularly and the pattern was changed every 12 runs. In this way the rehab was to perform the complex motor task; it was not simply exercise. Compared to pre-injury, animals after SCI were much slower, poorly coordinated, and less motivated to walk across the ladder. Rats were encouraged to cross the ladder (nudged from behind or tapped on their tail) and, after each run, were given sugar water. Forelimb performance was videotaped and analyzed for errors once at the end of each week except for week 1 of rehab, where we also filmed on day 1 of rehab to obtain a Pre-rehab score. Pre-rehab was not recorded on a separate day to prevent the rats from receiving an extra day of training. Error rates were calculated at the end of each week as described above.

CST anterograde tracing
After all behavioral tests were conducted, descending CST axons were traced anterogradely. Animals were placed in a stereotaxic frame, the screws holding the head cap in place were loosened, gently removing the entire head cap along with the cortical electrodes, thereby exposing the skull. The bilateral craniotomies were cleared of reactive tissue. We confirmed at this time that the electrodes appeared not to have caused any dural damage. To trace the CST bilaterally, seven biotinylated dextran amine (BDA) injections were made in each hemisphere (300nL/injection; BDA: 10,000MW; Molecular Probes; 10% in 0.1 M PBS) at the listed coordinates (AP: 0.5mm ML: 2.0mm; AP: 0.5mm ML:2.8mm; AP:0.5mm ML:3.9mm; AP:1.5 ML:3.5; AP:1.5 ML:2.5; AP:2.02 ML:2.5 and AP:2.02 ML:3.5); each at a depth of 1.5mm and an injection rate of 2nL/sec. BDA injections were made by piercing the dura with the beveled 35 ga. injection needle. BDA was injected slowly over a period of 3 mins and the needle remained in the cortex for an additional 2 mins before withdrawal to ensure no leakage. Animals were allowed to survive for two weeks after tracer injection.

PA anterograde tracing and retrograde motoneuron tracing
Seven days before perfusion cholera toxin B-fragment (CTB; 1%, 10μl; List Biologicals) was bilaterally injected into the extensor carpi radialis muscle, using a Hamilton syringe, to anterogradely label PA axons in the spinal gray matter as well as retrogradely label motoneurons in the ventral horn. CTB was tinted with Evan’s Blue Dye to visualize it inside the muscle, intramuscular CTB injections were made slowly (10 secs) and the needle was slowly withdrawn from the muscle to minimize leakage. Every effort was made to ensure that the injection on each side were the same. This was verified by counting the number of retrogradely-labeled motoneurons.

Tissue Preparation and staining
Animals were euthanized with Euthasol (1mL IP) and transcardially perfused with saline (300mL) followed by 4% paraformaldehyde (500mL) by opening the thoracic cavity and cannulating the left ventricular apex. The spinal cord was dissected from the vertebrae and removed from the dura, post-fixed in 4% paraformaldehyde in room temperature for 3 hours, then transferred in 20% sucrose for 48 hours in 4° temperature. Tissue was transversely cut at 40μm with a sliding microtome (frozen sections). C2 spinal segments were used to visualize BDA-traced CST axons rostral to the lesion and to count axons to calibrate tracer efficacy, and C6–7 was used for analysis caudal to the lesion. To visualize BDA staining, free-floating sections were incubated in phosphate-buffered (pH 7.4) saline containing 1% avidin-biotin complex reagent (ABC Kit; Vector Laboratories), followed either by the chromogen diaminobenzidine (DAB, Sigma) for rostral sections or streptavidin conjugated to Cy3 (Jackson ImmunoResearch) for caudal sections.Staining for CTB was performed with primary antibody goat anti-CTB (1:1000; List Biologicals) and secondary donkey anti-goat conjugated to FITC. Vesicular glutamate transporter 1 (VGlut1) was localized using a primary anti-VGlut1 antibody (1:10; NeuroMab) and a secondary donkey anti-mouse conjugated to Cy5.

Cavity Size Analysis
The bilateral cervical contusion produces a central cavity that damages most of the dorsal columns, including all of the dorsal CST, but spares dorsolateral and ventral CST projections (
Tuszynski and Steward, 2012
), as shown in the representative section (
Figure 1C
). This type of injury is inherently more variable compared to complete and partial spinal transections (
Anderson et al., 2009
). The size and location of the injury affects the amount and type of spared axons, respectively, and can therefore be a source of variability in functional recovery and response to treatment (
Hurd et al., 2013
). To measure cavity size, the postmortem C4 contused area was serially cut into transverse sections (40 μm) using a sliding microtome, directly mounted on glass slides and stained with Hematoxylin and Eosin (H&E). The 5 serial sections in the epicenter of the lesion, which also had the largest cavity, were analyzed by trained laboratory personnel, blinded to animal treatment group, using an unbiased stereological technique (Cavalieri Probe; Stereo Investigator; MBF Bioscience, Williston, Vermont, USA). The lesioned tissue sections were viewed under 10x magnification using the program’s live imaging mode. The software creates a grid that overlays the entire tissue (50 μm between each grid point). All grid points inside the lesion cavity were marked. Lesion cavity size is then calculated from the total number of marked grid points and the distance between each in a 3-dimensional orientation. The calculated mean area of each cavity was corrected for the respective section’s surface area.

CST anatomical data acquisition analysis
Analyses were performed by trained laboratory personnel blinded to animal treatment group. Sections caudal to the injury were imaged using a Zeiss LSM 880 meta confocal microscopy at 20x magnification. A montage of images was collected to visualize all labeled axons. A Z-stack was captured with a 4×5 tile at 20x magnification to visualize spared CST fibers in the entire gray matter. We manually traced the full length of all labeled axons in the gray matter using the program Neurolucida (MBF Bioscience, Williston, Vermont USA). It was important to examine CST axonal length bilaterally in the gray matter because both the injury and rehabilitation (stepping on the horizontal ladder) were bilateral. CST axon labelling can be influenced by tracer efficacy, such as injection size and uptake and transport of BDA by cortical neurons. To ensure that potential differences in caudal CST length were not due to variability in tracing efficacy, caudal CST axonal length was normalized to the total number of BDA-labelled CST axons in the dorsal columns rostral to the injury. To quantify rostral CST fibers, as described in our previous studies (
Carmel et al., 2010
;
Song et al., 2016
;
Zareen et al., 2017
), we used an unbiased stereological technique (Optical Dissector; Stereo Investigator; MBF Bioscience, Williston, Vermont USA) under 40x magnification to count BDA-labelled CST fibers in 75 × 75 μm bins.

PA, motoneuron and VGlut1 anatomical data acquisition and analyses
Images of the gray matter of the caudal cervical enlargement were captured using confocal microscopy under 10x magnification for bilateral PA analysis. Since this was an optical density assay, the same microscope laser settings were used for all sections. Micrographs were analyzed using ImageJ software (JAVA 1.8.0_112; NIH) and the background was thresholded to eliminate non-specific labelling to accurately measure intra-axonal CTB. In order to make sure that the same areas of each section were analyzed, we divided the dorsoventral extent of the gray matter into 3 equal quadrants corresponding to the dorsal horn, intermediate zone and ventral horn. The dorsal horn and intermediate zone were assayed for PA labelling. For each section, the total amount of bilateral PA density was summed and normalized for the number of motor neurons in the ventral horn. Because it is not possible to distinguish between transganglionic (anterograde afferent) CTB labeling and motoneuron (retrograde) recurrent axon labeling, we used VGlut1 to visualize PA terminal synapses contacting ECR motoneurons. Large-diameter PA fibers use the glutamate vesicular transporter VGlut1 (
Alvarez et al., 2004
) that can be used as a marker for the monosynaptic 1A afferent terminals on MNs. The only other source of VGlut1 in the spinal cord is in the CST terminals. However, there are no CST terminals in the motor pools (
Jiang et al., 2016
). Moreover, 1a afferent terminals, where present, are 6-times larger than CST terminals (4.0 μm versus 0.67 μm) . Individual CTB-labelled ECR motoneurons, and surrounding VGlut1, were captured under 63x magnification using high-resolution confocal microscopy. Images (z-stacks; 1 μm optical sections) were transferred to Neurolucida and motoneurons were reconstructed by drawing contours around the soma and proximal dendrites and counting the number of VGlut1 boutons contacting motoneurons in each section. The tracing data files were transferred to Neurolucida Explorer to obtain the sum of VGlut1 and the mean area of the corresponding motoneuron, which was used as a normalization factor.

Heat Map Analysis of CST axons and PA labeling caudal to C4 contusion
To determine the location of CST and PA labeling in each animal group, we constructed average topographic color-coded heat maps for gray matter CST axon length and PA axon density caudal to the injury, similar to our prior studies (e.g.,
Brus-Ramer et al., 2007
). Axon labeling data were exported as individual sections and combined into a single layered file (Adobe Photoshop 2020). Each section was aligned with one another according to fiduciary marks. The aligned layers were then exported as individual TIFF files for each section and average heat maps were constructed, as in our prior studies, using custom programs written in Matlab (MathWorks). For PA afferent gray matter terminations, thresholded PA density images from ImageJ were exported and processed as for the CST axons. For further quantification of CST axons, individual section data were analyzed using custom programs written in Matlab (MathWorks) to compute the dorsoventral distribution of labeling, as in prior studies (
Friel and Martin, 2007
;
Salimi et al., 2008
). We determined the amount of labeling for both sides of the spinal cord, from the dorsal horn to the ventral horn. Since, section size varied slightly from animal-to-animal and within animals, the distribution was interpolated to obtain 100 data points and we constructed an average for all animals in each treatment group (see
Fig 4D
,
E
). For individual animal analyses, we regressed the average amount of CST label within particular gray matter territories, as the ratio of regional label to total label, with the motor outcome (absolute ladder walking error rate at week 6).
